  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Emergency Victim Assistance and Risk Education for conflict-affected populations in Qayyarah</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="2">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Since the offensive launched in October 2016 to retake the Islamic State (IS)-occupied city of Mosul, violent clashes and military operations have triggered mass waves of internal displacement and a rapidly unfolding humanitarian crisis. Levels of mine/Explosive Remnants of War (ERW) and Improvised Explosive Device (IED) contamination in areas retaken from IS are unprecedented, and amongst displaced populations are high numbers of trauma casualties, including mine/ERW/IED survivors, other persons with disabilities and persons with injuries from other causes requiring specialist assistance. Coupled with this are extreme levels of psychological distress among displaced and returning populations, compounded by a severe deficit of services catering to Mental Health and Psychosocial Support (MHPSS) needs.

HI will respond to these needs through victim assistance and risk education activities in camp and out-of-camp settings in Qayyarah, deploying one Risk Education (RE) team through a national partner, and two Victim Assistance (VA) teams  to reduce the immediate threat of explosive hazards and address identified needs for physical and functional rehabilitation and psychosocial support. These teams will provide risk awareness messages with a particular focus on schools as well as deliver emergency physical and functional rehabilitation, caregiver advice and psychosocial support to Persons with Disabilities (PwD), Persons with Injuries (PwI) and other conflict-affected populations, representing a continuation and scale up of Handicap International&#x2019;s (HI) existing capacity in the area of intervention.</narrative>
  </description>
